Besides the emphatic profession of the historian’s obligation to impar- tiality‚ we have to note the full belief of Tacitus that he has the means of reaching truth, by weighing in the scales of justice the indiscriminate praise or censure of earlier writers. He is more conscious of the difficulty of writing on the Flavian Caesars, to whom he was personally indebted ³, than on the period covered by the Annals, one in which, as he believed, ‘the grounds of resentment or partiality were far removed from him ⁴.¹
